<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText">Hi Tom,<br />
<br />
&gt; To use the ObservableListContentProvider I need to provide an <br />
&gt; IObservableList. However my list is not one of those and I don't <br />
&gt; particularly want to make it so - it seems odd to use <br />
&gt; PropertyChangeListeners for non-collection properties and  <br />
&gt; IObservableCollections for collection properties.<br />
<br />
You can use<br />
WritableList list = new WritableList(yourmarktdomain.getMarkets(), <br />
Markt.class);<br />
<br />
viewer.setInput(list);<br />
<br />
You would have to extend your by this method to get the initial list for <br />
WritableList:<br />
<br />
List&lt;Market&gt; TransientMarketService.getMarkets() {<br />
   return markets;<br />
}<br />
<br />
Then the writeable List will directly operate on your markts list.<br />
Be aware though, that changes in the TransientMarketService markets list <br />
are not visible to the observer. Only the other way around.<br />
<br />
I have an update job running in the background that updates my View <br />
Domain Model, what happens to be a Subclass of ObservableList. That way <br />
any changes you make in the View Model reflect into the Model as well as <br />
in the UI.<br />
<br />
Its only a thin wrapper around your Domain Model and worth the effort:<br />
<br />
class ViewModelOfMarkets extends WritableList {<br />
   public ViewModelOfMarkets(TransientMarketService service) {<br />
     super(service.getMarkets(), Market.class);<br />
   }<br />
<br />
   public void create(Market market) {<br />
     add(market); // Updates service market list, fires UI change event<br />
   }<br />
}<br />
<br />
You get the idea. Be aware that changes to observed list may only occur <br />
from withing the same realm they were initially created in.<br />
If you not sure in which realm you are operating and can be called from <br />
do this:<br />
<br />
public void create(Market market) {<br />
     getRealm().asyncExec(new Runnable() {<br />
        void run() {<br />
           add(market);<br />
           // Updates service market list, fires UI change event<br />
        }<br />
     });<br />
}<br />
<br />
<br />
Enjoy,<br />
Phil</span>


