<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText"><b>Originally posted by:</b> thomas.x.hughes.jpmorgan.com<br />
<br />
Thanks for the reply.<br />
<br />
I think I understand why you don't use plain PropertyChangeListeners - <br />
They don't give enough info. For instance it's impossible to tell the <br />
difference between setting an item to null and a deletion, and also adding <br />
an item and setting a previously null item to a new value.<br />
<br />
For single valued attributes (strings, doubles etc) in your domain model <br />
do you recommend using PropertyChangeListeners or some other eclipse <br />
databinding construct?<br />
<br />
Comments on using ObservableList :<br />
 1 No generics. Can live with this.<br />
 2 Not consistent with PropertyChangeListener idiom.<br />
 3 Not possible to use when the list isn't always in memory. <br />
<br />
An example of 3 could be my MarketService example. (Market is a domain <br />
object, it's details are unimportant). This is a service layer object  (in <br />
fact an interface). In the example implementation in the previous post, <br />
TransientMarketService, holds all the Markets in memory in a List, so <br />
using an ObservableList is not a problem. This implementation is for <br />
testing. Real implementations will write to persistent store and perhaps <br />
do caching. There is no master list here, I can't use an ObservableList - <br />
well I could but I would have to use some kind of lazy load proxy.<br />
<br />
I think an alternative solution could involve extending <br />
PropertyChangeEvent to include the extra info required. <br />
ListPropertyChangeEvent for example. This would allow usage with any List, <br />
would allow generics, would be consitent with PropertyChangeListener idiom <br />
and would be possible to use when the list isn't always in memory. <br />
<br />
Tom</span>


