<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText">Tom Hughes wrote:<br />
<br />
&gt; For single valued attributes (strings, doubles etc) in your domain model <br />
&gt; do you recommend using PropertyChangeListeners or some other eclipse <br />
&gt; databinding construct?<br />
<br />
OberservableValue would be a good start. If you just wanna show the <br />
values in a label of a List/Tree you can try ObservableMapLabel Provider <br />
witch directly connects to Bean objects and reads the current values.<br />
<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; Comments on using ObservableList :<br />
&gt; 1 No generics. Can live with this.<br />
<br />
Unfortunatly the whole codebase of Eclipse is backward compatible with <br />
Java 1.4 thats why we do not see any of the new Generics features here.<br />
<br />
&gt; 2 Not consistent with PropertyChangeListener idiom.<br />
<br />
You can always add this on top of your own subclass of OberservableList.<br />
<br />
&gt; 3 Not possible to use when the list isn't always in memory.<br />
<br />
I was facing the same problem recently. I have bunch of orders that are <br />
fetched from a database. This should happen constantly in the <br />
background. So I had a thread that was fetching those orders and <br />
reported new orders to listeners. However this was like reinventing the <br />
weel cause this is already implemented in eclipse databinding now.<br />
And since the fetching of new orders only occurs to present them in the <br />
UI (and not to do some background work on them) this service could very <br />
well just use the facilities provided by eclipse. So now a Workbench Job <br />
is running in the background when the view for orders is opened. It <br />
fetches a new List of jobs from the server and builds a ListDiff from <br />
this and sends this diff to all listeners. Those listeners update the <br />
interface, cause mostly they are just ObservableListContentProviders. If <br />
you remember to switch into the same realm as the listeners its working <br />
flawlessly and is reasonable decoupled from the GUI.<br />
<br />
This service object could also just run without any GUI listeners attached.<br />
<br />
Phil</span>


