<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText">&gt; 2 Not consistent with PropertyChangeListener idiom.<br />
<br />
What do you mean by this?  PropertyChangeListeners are part of the <br />
JavaBean spec.  This isn't the only API/framework for change listeners. <br />
  DataBinding is meant to be used with JavaBeans, EMF, SWT, or any type <br />
of object/specification that fires change events.  Observables are an <br />
abstraction for change events that we adapt specific implementations to. <br />
  Also it wouldn't be correct for us to make our API <br />
PropertyChangeListeners as the bean API is very old and lacks a lot of <br />
the features necessary to observe all types of changes.<br />
<br />
&gt; 3 Not possible to use when the list isn't always in memory.<br />
<br />
&gt; An example of 3 could be my MarketService example. (Market is a domain <br />
&gt; object, it's details are unimportant). This is a service layer object  <br />
&gt; (in fact an interface). In the example implementation in the previous <br />
&gt; post, TransientMarketService, holds all the Markets in memory in a List, <br />
&gt; so using an ObservableList is not a problem. This implementation is for <br />
&gt; testing. Real implementations will write to persistent store and perhaps <br />
&gt; do caching. There is no master list here, I can't use an ObservableList <br />
&gt; - well I could but I would have to use some kind of lazy load proxy.<br />
<br />
What could we do here to help you out?  The API of IObservableList <br />
provides a flag and listeners to know if the list is stale (is <br />
changing).  In existing implementations we don't use this as the list <br />
implementation is in memory as you point out.  But if you have needs <br />
above and beyond this and it is something that could be abstracted out <br />
please log a bug and we can discuss it.<br />
<br />
-brad</span>


