<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText">&gt; Maybe I should be more precise. They must be called from the same realm <br />
&gt; they were initially created in. Thats why I always do a <br />
&gt; list.getRealm().asyncExec() to modify them. Which is, quite error prone.<br />
<br />
Yes, that is true.  What is error prone about it?  Possibly forgetting <br />
to do this?  The reason it is done this way is that the normal means of <br />
synchronization lead to dead locks when using the observer pattern.  For <br />
more information on how we got here see bug 116920[1].<br />
<br />
&gt; Are there any guidelines from the eclipse databinding team regarding this?<br />
<br />
The wiki has probably the most up to date guideline in regards to why <br />
this is necessary and how to access observables in the correct realm[2]. <br />
  One tip is that Bindings handle this by default and if you can use a <br />
Binding, even for just a direct copy from one to the other, it might be <br />
worth it for the use case.<br />
<br />
-brad<br />
<br />
[1] <a href="https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=116920" target="_blank">https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=116920</a><br />
[2] <a href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Realm" target="_blank">http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Realm</a></span>


