<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText"><b>Originally posted by:</b> tomatqanda.hotmail.com<br />
<br />
Thanks Brad. <br />
<br />
I have read those documents, and in fact a presentation model is the style <br />
of ui I'm going to create. <br />
<br />
Presentation model &lt;-&gt; swt widgets seems well covered in the code and in <br />
the snippets. <br />
I'm currently exploring the domain model &lt;-&gt; presentation model linkage. <br />
<br />
(1)The obvious route seems to be the java bean standard and property <br />
change listeners. The main problem as discussed is that this doesn't <br />
support notification of addition and removal from a collection.<br />
<br />
(2)Another alternative would be to use ObservableList (or Set, I'm just <br />
List as an example) in my domain objects. The main problem seems to be <br />
exposing the list. Normally I would copy any list exposed to preserve <br />
encapsulation. Something like :<br />
<br />
private List people;<br />
<br />
List getPeople() <br />
{<br />
  return new ArrayList(people);<br />
{<br />
<br />
(I'm sure you know this already, not meaning to be condescending, just <br />
clear.)<br />
If I want to vend my observable list so it can participate in databinding, <br />
I can't copy it, I need to give a reference to the actual list I'm <br />
updating.<br />
<br />
(3)Another solution I'm considering is to extend PropertyChangeEvent to <br />
support notification of addition and removal from a collection. My domain <br />
objects would then fire PropertyChangeEvents in the normal idiom, firing <br />
the extended event when dealing with collections. I then build an adapter <br />
which could listen to the extended PropertyChangeEvents and apply the <br />
updates to a WritableList. <br />
<br />
<br />
The reason for this post is that none of these seem ideal solutions. <br />
Number 1, actually isn't a solution as it doesn't work. Number 2 means I <br />
lose encapsulation of my collection attributes (maybe this is not too bad, <br />
Hibernate more or less imposes this on you too). Number 3 is an unproven <br />
solution which involves extra infrastructure. <br />
<br />
I hope this makes some sort of sense and I am interested in your (or <br />
anyone else's) views on this.<br />
<br />
thanks, Tom</span>


