<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText">Hi,<br />
<br />
That really sounds interesting. I think I'm in the process of <br />
integrating EMF into my current Databinding-Framework where I'm in the <br />
process creating an description language to bind models (POJOs generated <br />
e.g. by hibernate, ... ).<br />
<br />
<a href="http://publicsvn.bestsolution.at/repos/java/at.bestsolution.dataforms.test/trunk/forms/mainform-test/binding.xbl" target="_blank"> http://publicsvn.bestsolution.at/repos/java/at.bestsolution. dataforms.test/trunk/forms/mainform-test/binding.xbl</a><br />
<br />
Tom<br />
<br />
Ed Merks schrieb:<br />
&gt; Tom,<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; I feel like a salesman jumping into this thread, but I should point out <br />
&gt; that EMF generates models that fully support notification.  Even <br />
&gt; multi-valued properties are surfaced as lists that are editable and will <br />
&gt; notify.  The notification support is so complete that you can attach a <br />
&gt; ChangeRecorder to an model instance that records all notifications and <br />
&gt; can convert them to a ChangeDescription, which can them be applied to <br />
&gt; undo all the changes (and reapplied to redo the changes).  It's a very <br />
&gt; handy way to support a dialog with cancel or to implement undo/redo.  <br />
&gt; It's also an interesting way to interact with a server where you might <br />
&gt; want to send back only a description of the changes you've made; a <br />
&gt; change description is also a model instance and can be serialized to and <br />
&gt; from XML just like any other EMF model instance.  You might find that <br />
&gt; EMF will generate much of your application<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt;     The Eclipse Modeling Framework Overview<br />
&gt;     &lt;<a href="http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/*checkout*/org.eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/references/overview/EMF.html" target="_blank"> http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/*checkout*/org .eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/references/overview/EMF .html</a>&gt;<br />
&gt;     The EMF Edit Framework Overview<br />
&gt;     &lt;<a href="http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/*checkout*/org.eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/references/overview/EMF.Edit.html" target="_blank"> http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/*checkout*/org .eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/references/overview/EMF .Edit.html</a>&gt;<br />
&gt;     Tutorial: Generating an EMF Model using XML Schema<br />
&gt;     &lt;<a href="http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/*checkout*/org.eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/tutorials/xlibmod/xlibmod.html" target="_blank"> http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/*checkout*/org .eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/tutorials/xlibmod/xlibm od.html</a>&gt;<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; And if you want a GEF-based UI, <a href="http://www.eclipse.org/gmf/" target="_blank">http://www.eclipse.org/gmf/</a> <br />
&gt; &lt;<a href="http://www.eclipse.org/gmf/" target="_blank">http://www.eclipse.org/gmf/</a>&gt;can generate that too.  Unfortunately we <br />
&gt; won't have time to integrate with the data binding work until next <br />
&gt; release there there are patches in this bugzilla which are a start:<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt;     <a href="https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=75625" target="_blank">https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=75625</a><br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; Tom Hughes wrote:<br />
&gt;&gt; Thanks Brad.<br />
&gt;&gt; I have read those documents, and in fact a presentation model is the <br />
&gt;&gt; style of ui I'm going to create.<br />
&gt;&gt; Presentation model &lt;-&gt; swt widgets seems well covered in the code and <br />
&gt;&gt; in the snippets. I'm currently exploring the domain model &lt;-&gt; <br />
&gt;&gt; presentation model linkage.<br />
&gt;&gt; (1)The obvious route seems to be the java bean standard and property <br />
&gt;&gt; change listeners. The main problem as discussed is that this doesn't <br />
&gt;&gt; support notification of addition and removal from a collection.<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; (2)Another alternative would be to use ObservableList (or Set, I'm <br />
&gt;&gt; just List as an example) in my domain objects. The main problem seems <br />
&gt;&gt; to be exposing the list. Normally I would copy any list exposed to <br />
&gt;&gt; preserve encapsulation. Something like :<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; private List people;<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; List getPeople() {<br />
&gt;&gt;  return new ArrayList(people);<br />
&gt;&gt; {<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; (I'm sure you know this already, not meaning to be condescending, just <br />
&gt;&gt; clear.)<br />
&gt;&gt; If I want to vend my observable list so it can participate in <br />
&gt;&gt; databinding, I can't copy it, I need to give a reference to the actual <br />
&gt;&gt; list I'm updating.<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; (3)Another solution I'm considering is to extend PropertyChangeEvent <br />
&gt;&gt; to support notification of addition and removal from a collection. My <br />
&gt;&gt; domain objects would then fire PropertyChangeEvents in the normal <br />
&gt;&gt; idiom, firing the extended event when dealing with collections. I then <br />
&gt;&gt; build an adapter which could listen to the extended <br />
&gt;&gt; PropertyChangeEvents and apply the updates to a WritableList.<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; The reason for this post is that none of these seem ideal solutions. <br />
&gt;&gt; Number 1, actually isn't a solution as it doesn't work. Number 2 means <br />
&gt;&gt; I lose encapsulation of my collection attributes (maybe this is not <br />
&gt;&gt; too bad, Hibernate more or less imposes this on you too). Number 3 is <br />
&gt;&gt; an unproven solution which involves extra infrastructure.<br />
&gt;&gt; I hope this makes some sort of sense and I am interested in your (or <br />
&gt;&gt; anyone else's) views on this.<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt; thanks, Tom<br />
&gt;&gt;<br />
