<tr><td colspan="2" class="MsgR3">
<span class="MsgBodyText">Tom Hughes wrote:<br />
&gt; Thanks Brad.<br />
&gt; I have read those documents, and in fact a presentation model is the <br />
&gt; style of ui I'm going to create.<br />
&gt; Presentation model &lt;-&gt; swt widgets seems well covered in the code and in <br />
&gt; the snippets. I'm currently exploring the domain model &lt;-&gt; presentation <br />
&gt; model linkage.<br />
&gt; (1)The obvious route seems to be the java bean standard and property <br />
&gt; change listeners. The main problem as discussed is that this doesn't <br />
&gt; support notification of addition and removal from a collection.<br />
&gt;<br />
<br />
Many domain model generators (generating a java bean from a RDBMS like <br />
in Hibernate) do not generate property change events during code <br />
generation and use standard java collection objects which are magically <br />
replaced with ORM-specific collections to help manage persistence.  Not <br />
all do however.<br />
<br />
If you have a list of domain objects and want to display them either <br />
using observable lists directly in your domain model (WritableList) or <br />
taking a standard java list with WritableList when you need to set the <br />
input of your viewer should work.  The ObservableListContentProvider <br />
listens for list changes directly.  Check out the code from <br />
ObservableListContentProvider:<br />
<br />
observableList.addListChangeListener(listener);<br />
<br />
and then updates the viewer when the list changes.  If you want<br />
to add to the list in the background, you need to add to the <br />
WriteableList not to the list return directly by your domain model <br />
unless your domain model returns a WritableList.  I think this is the <br />
heart of your (2).<br />
<br />
The PresentationModel design pattern is good at covering this up for you <br />
and simplifying your use of SWT data binding.  It can create models for <br />
you behind the scene of the right type and act as a &quot;observable value <br />
builder.&quot;  Jgoodies has does extremely well in my opinion.  Since one<br />
of the &quot;visuals&quot; in your GUI as well as needs for updating in another <br />
thread is a WriteableList, add a method to the presentation model to <br />
retrieve a writeable list and other methods to retrieve property models <br />
directly for binding:<br />
<br />
class SWTPresentationModel {<br />
	<br />
	YourBean bean;<br />
<br />
	public SWTPresentationModel(Object bean)...<br />
<br />
<br />
	public WritableValue getModel(String property) {<br />
		return createWritableValueUsingSWTBeansBindingStuff(bean, property);<br />
	}<br />
<br />
	public WritableList getMasterList() {<br />
		return WritableList(bean.PlainOldList);<br />
		// or<br />
		return WritableList(yourServiceObject.getList());<br />
	}<br />
<br />
}<br />
<br />
then you can use:<br />
<br />
	bcontext.addBinding(pm.getModel(&quot;name&quot;), someSWTGUIEndPoint); // or <br />
whatever<br />
	 yourBackgroundService.setListToAddDeleteTo(pm.getMasterList( ));<br />
<br />
<br />
The jgoodies PresentationModel is actually much more useful and <br />
incredible utilitarian as well when combined with a SelectionInList <br />
concept...you can bypass all the master detail databinding setup in a <br />
very trivial way.  If you make a PresentationModel a WritableValue as <br />
well you can use it in a variety of ways around database-oriented <br />
programs.  For example, when you set the PM's bean to another bean you <br />
can manually force the GUI to update even if your domain model does not <br />
automatically propagate change events. It helps manage domain models <br />
that are not &quot;perfect&quot; and setup for binding to start with. Also, if <br />
your background process writing to the list needs to know when the <br />
entire list object has changed, you can make the PM class a writeable <br />
value, listen for &quot;value&quot; changes (which is the bean in the PM class) <br />
and then call getMasterList() again. The background process then just <br />
adds a value change listener to the PM directly although there are other <br />
ways to do this as well.<br />
<br />
This removes all UI thoughts from your domain model as Brad indicated.<br />
<br />
Just remember that if you code something, SWT does not use standard java <br />
beans PLC (property change listeners) so you have to be mindful of which <br />
PLC-framework you are using, standard java or SWT.<br />
<br />
<br />
&gt; (2)Another alternative would be to use ObservableList (or Set, I'm just <br />
&gt; List as an example) in my domain objects. The main problem seems to be <br />
&gt; exposing the list. Normally I would copy any list exposed to preserve <br />
&gt; encapsulation. Something like :<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; private List people;<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; List getPeople() {<br />
&gt;  return new ArrayList(people);<br />
&gt; {<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; (I'm sure you know this already, not meaning to be condescending, just <br />
&gt; clear.)<br />
&gt; If I want to vend my observable list so it can participate in <br />
&gt; databinding, I can't copy it, I need to give a reference to the actual <br />
&gt; list I'm updating.<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; (3)Another solution I'm considering is to extend PropertyChangeEvent to <br />
&gt; support notification of addition and removal from a collection. My <br />
&gt; domain objects would then fire PropertyChangeEvents in the normal idiom, <br />
&gt; firing the extended event when dealing with collections. I then build an <br />
&gt; adapter which could listen to the extended PropertyChangeEvents and <br />
&gt; apply the updates to a WritableList.<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; The reason for this post is that none of these seem ideal solutions. <br />
&gt; Number 1, actually isn't a solution as it doesn't work. Number 2 means I <br />
&gt; lose encapsulation of my collection attributes (maybe this is not too <br />
&gt; bad, Hibernate more or less imposes this on you too). Number 3 is an <br />
&gt; unproven solution which involves extra infrastructure.<br />
&gt; I hope this makes some sort of sense and I am interested in your (or <br />
&gt; anyone else's) views on this.<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; thanks, Tom<br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; <br />
&gt; <br />
&gt;</span>


