&gt;&gt;&gt; &lt;<a href="http://www.eclipse.org/gmf/" target="_blank">http://www.eclipse.org/gmf/</a>&gt;can generate that too.  Unfortunately we <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt; won't have time to integrate with the data binding work until next <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt; release there there are patches in this bugzilla which are a start:<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;     <a href="https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=75625" target="_blank">https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=75625</a><br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt; Tom Hughes wrote:<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Thanks Brad.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I have read those documents, and in fact a presentation model is the <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; style of ui I'm going to create.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Presentation model &lt;-&gt; swt widgets seems well covered in the code <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; and in the snippets. I'm currently exploring the domain model &lt;-&gt; <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; presentation model linkage.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; (1)The obvious route seems to be the java bean standard and property <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; change listeners. The main problem as discussed is that this doesn't <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; support notification of addition and removal from a collection.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; (2)Another alternative would be to use ObservableList (or Set, I'm <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; just List as an example) in my domain objects. The main problem <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; seems to be exposing the list. Normally I would copy any list <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; exposed to preserve encapsulation. Something like :<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; private List people;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; List getPeople() {<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;  return new ArrayList(people);<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; {<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; (I'm sure you know this already, not meaning to be condescending, <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; just clear.)<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; If I want to vend my observable list so it can participate in <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; databinding, I can't copy it, I need to give a reference to the <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; actual list I'm updating.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; (3)Another solution I'm considering is to extend PropertyChangeEvent <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; to support notification of addition and removal from a collection. <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; My domain objects would then fire PropertyChangeEvents in the normal <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; idiom, firing the extended event when dealing with collections. I <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; then build an adapter which could listen to the extended <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; PropertyChangeEvents and apply the updates to a WritableList.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; The reason for this post is that none of these seem ideal solutions. <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Number 1, actually isn't a solution as it doesn't work. Number 2 <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; means I lose encapsulation of my collection attributes (maybe this <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; is not too bad, Hibernate more or less imposes this on you too). <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Number 3 is an unproven solution which involves extra infrastructure.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I hope this makes some sort of sense and I am interested in your (or <br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; anyone else's) views on this.<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; thanks, Tom<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;&gt;&gt;<br />
&gt;</span>


<div class="SmallText"><p class="fr"><a href="index.php?t=report&amp;msg_id=315226&amp;" rel="nofollow">Report message to a moderator</a></p></div>
</td></tr>
